Students are expected to be able to:
• Debunk how sexualities are shaped by larger social forces and therefore socially constructed;
• Understand the instability, plurality and diversity of sexualities;
• Show an understanding of how sexualities can be analysed and researched from different angles;
• Critically examine how sexualities intersect with social categories, such as class, age, race and ethnicity, in producing social structure;
• Analyse how sexualities are bound up with struggles over rights and entitlement;
• Critically assess social messages regarding sexualities and question the extent to which they themselves agree or disagree with the conventional ‘definitions’ and ‘norms’ in society.

At the end of this class students are expected to be able to:
(1) understand major issues of global orders and global governance;
(2) discuss them in the historical context in which they were developed;
(3) identify their contributions to thinking and methods in global society;
(4) trace how concepts have evolved through historical circumstances, theoretical debates, and methodological innovations;
(5) recognize the major theoretical and policy challenges of global governance, social problems and globalization;
(6) prepare for further understanding of relevant themes and debates in the public and private sectors, including but not limited to such emerging fields as ESG investment, ESG reporting, carbon trading, and carbon neutral policy in Hong Kong and Mainland China.

Knowledge Domain
(1) understand the role of Sociology in contributing to our knowledge of social order and its changes;
(2) apply basic concepts derived from sociological theories in the understanding of social phenomenon;
Skills Domain
(3) master basic qualitative and quantitative methods in Sociology;
(4) think critically;
(5) critically reflect on the role of artificial intelligence in social research, considering its implications for data analysis, ethical practice, and the potential merits of both its use and non-use.
Values Domain
(6) reflect on his or her own value position and appreciate:
sociology as a useful and meaningful perspective on social reality and individual biography;
the importance of ethics, honesty, and transparency in research and academic settings; and
the importance of sociological analyses for reflection of value positions and life choices.

