By the end of the course, you should be able to:
conceptualize a research problem and formulate good research questions;
develop the appropriate research design that will help you find answers to your research questions;
collect your own data using a variety of methods;
understand both qualitative and quantitative data analysis techniques that are most relevant to your own research questions and data;
present and discuss your own findings verbally and in writing;
evaluate the work of other academics as well as the use of social research in general;
appreciate different ways to observe and analyze the social world.

After going through this course, the students are expected to achieve the following goals, namely
1)attain a condensed bird’s eye view of the trajectory and identity of the discipline of Sociology;
2)comprehend the fundamental theoretical perspectives based upon which new research questions and agenda can be formulated;
3)assimilate the insights of distinguished sociologists as a rich source for intellectual cultivation and personal growth.

