Coser, Lewis, Masters of Sociological Thought 2nd edition (HBJ Press);
Ritzer, George, Sociological Theory 6th edition (McGraw-Hill); and
Zeitlin, Irving, Ideology and Development of Sociological Theory 7th edition (Prentice Hall)

courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, the students should be able to:
1. Describe the role of sociological theories in understanding social problems and inequalities, and show how these theories reflect the historical context of the times and cultures in which they were developed;
2. Reflect on the diversity of values, interests, and positions in terms of social problems and inequalities, based on the theoretical assumptions and fundamental interrelationships of sociological analyses;
3. Analyze commonly-held views regarding social problems and inequalities, and suggest alternative or potentially opposing explanations and hypotheses; and
4. Apply sociological perspectives to the analysis of real-life instances of social problems and resulting inequalities.

Upon the completion of the course, students are expected
1. to have a basic understanding of general theories of sociology of education;
2. to be able to reflect on the meaning and significance of school and schooling experiences in a sociological way;
3. to relate their own experience to the concepts and theories learned in the course.

1. To understand different forms and sources of social inequalities;
2. To become familiarized with major sociological theories in class analysis
3. To reflect critically how our everyday life is influenced by class factors;
4. To be able to analyze social inequalities and class phenomena in the Chinese societies (such as Mainland China and Hong Kong)
